R Notebook

Problem

Business Tasks

Cyclistic is a fictional bike-share company inside Chicago. This company tasked us with the analysis of this question:
How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?
Lets break this business task into sub tasks:

  • Identify and categorize how users use Cyclistic services
  • See how those usage relate to casual riders and annual members
  • Identify usage differences and similarities between casual riders and annual members

Audience (stakeholders in bold):

  • Director of marketing
  • Part of analytics team
  • Cyclistic executives

Data sources:

  • Cyclistics first party data from the last 12 months: from march 22 to February 23 Cyclistic is a fictional company. The data is provided by Motivate International Inc.The data contain one row per users trip. The variables are about:

    • trips starting hour and location
    • trips ending hour and location
    • customers membership
    • bike type

    The used files are:

    • 2022MM-divvy-tripdata/2022MM-divvy-tripdata.csv with MM the month (03 to 12)
    • 202209-divvy-tripdata/202209-divvy-publictripdata.csv
    • 2022MM-divvy-tripdata/2022MM-divvy-tripdata.csv with MM the month (01 to 02)

  • Chicago ZIP boundaries Contains a map (shapefile) that represents the Chicago divided by ZIP areas

isTripFile <- function(filePath){
  readLines(filePath, n=1) %>% 
    grepl(pattern = "ride_id|trip_id") 
}
# testFileName <- "enterFileName"
# isTripFile(glue("{dataPath}/{testFileName}"))

coordinatesPrecision<- 3 #With 3 digits the coordinate precision is around 110m
chicagoBbox<-st_bbox(chicago_sf)

chicagoCoordinates <- expand.grid(seq(chicagoBbox$xmin, chicagoBbox$xmax, 0.1^coordinatesPrecision), seq(chicagoBbox$ymin, chicagoBbox$ymax, 0.1^coordinatesPrecision) ) %>% #Cartesian product of chicago lat and long arrays
  round(. ,coordinatesPrecision) %>%
  setnames(c("lng","lat")) %>% 
  mutate(lt = lat, lg= lng) %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lg","lt"), crs = 4326)

#Associate every coordinates in chicagoCoordinate to a zone
coordinateToZoneTable <- st_join(x=chicagoCoordinates, y=chicago_df, join = st_within, left=T) %>% #Coordinate to zone mapping
  drop_na() %>%
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  select(c(lat, lng, objectid))

rm(chicago_sf, chicagoCoordinates, chicagoBbox)

Data cleaning

Removed data:

  • duplicate trips
  • the trips that last for a minute or less because its a canceled trip
  • the trips that last for more than a day because its likely that the user forgot to return the bike
  • the trips that had starting or ending location outside of Chicago because thats not supposed to be possible
  • the trips with a duration that are in the 1% longest trips to make readable the graphs that have tripduration as an axis

Data modifications:

  • added tripduration
  • deteriorated the coordinates so that the possible number of coordinates inside Chicago is finite
  • added day of the week
  • added month
  • added Zip zoneIds for the trips starting location and ending location
  • ordered by station_name then by started_at
processedData <- tripData %>%
  drop_na(end_lat, end_lng) %>% #Drop trajects without end coordinates
  unique() %>% #Remove duplicates
  mutate(tripduration = difftime(ended_at, started_at)) %>%   #Add trips duration
  filter(tripduration>=60) %>% #Filter trip of less than 1min
  filter(tripduration<=86400)  #Filter trip of more than 1day
  
processedData <- processedData %>% 
  filter(tripduration<quantile(processedData$tripduration, probs = c(.99))) %>%   #Filter outliers
  mutate(day = (wday(started_at)-2)%%7 +1) %>% #Add day of the week
  mutate(month = month(started_at)) %>% #Add month of the year
  mutate(start_lat = round(start_lat, coordinatesPrecision) , start_lng = round(start_lng, coordinatesPrecision) , end_lat = round(end_lat, coordinatesPrecision) , end_lng = round(end_lng, coordinatesPrecision) ) %>%  #Deteriorate lat, long precision to have less distinct value
  merge(., coordinateToZoneTable, by.x=c("start_lat", "start_lng"), by.y = c("lat", "lng")) %>% #Add the zone id where the trip started. This also filter the trip that started outside of Chicago
  setnames(., "objectid", "startZoneId") %>% 
  merge(., coordinateToZoneTable, by.x=c("end_lat", "end_lng"), by.y = c("lat", "lng")) %>% #Add the zone id where the trip ended. This also filter the trip that ended outside of Chicago
  setnames(., "objectid", "endZoneId") %>%  
  setorderv(c("start_station_name","started_at"), c(1,1)) #Order data by station then start time
  
rm(tripData, coordinateToZoneTable)

Usage throughout the week

Casuals use Cyclistic a lot more during the weekend than during the workweek. On the opposite, members have a close to constant usage during the whole week but they use the service slightly more during the workweek than during the weekend.

Usage throughout the year

Casuals enjoy Cyclistic during the sunny months (more than 15% usage during June to august) and avoid it during the cold ones (less than 2.5% usage during the December to February).
Members follow the same trend but they are much more constant on their usage with only December under 4% usage, and no month above 12.5% usage.

Usage by location

Location alone

At first glance, both members and casuals make a similar usage of Cyclistic in term of location alone: they are both centered on the Lincoln park area of ZIP code 60614. However, by analyzing the difference between member usage we can see that:

  • casuals prefer Streeterville neighborhood, Lincoln park and South Loop a bit more

  • members prefer West Loop and Woodlawn a bit more

Those tendencies remain the same during the whole week, but get reinforced for Streeterville during the weekend.
We only display the graphs based on the trip ending zone because the graph based on trip beginning zone are similar.

#Function that plot:
#   - station usage in Chicago districts 
#   - station usage difference between user types in Chicago districts
plot_chicago_data_memberCasualDiff <- function(chicago_data, chicago_map, zoneType, contextualisation){
  customerTypeByZoneType <- chicago_data %>% 
    group_by(.data[[zoneType]], member_casual) %>%
    summarize(count = n()) %>% 
    pivot_wider(names_from = member_casual, values_from = count, values_fill = 0)
  
  chicago_map_with_customerTypeCount <- merge(chicago_map, customerTypeByZoneType, by.x=("objectid"), by.y=(zoneType))
  
  plots<-list()
    
  p<-ggplot(data = chicago_map_with_customerTypeCount) +
    geom_sf(aes(fill=((member+casual)/sum(member+casual))))+
    scale_fill_viridis_c(na.value = "pink",
                         labels = scales::percent_format(),
                         name = "% of usage")+
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))+
    labs(title = glue("Chicago zone usage {contextualisation}")) 
  plots[[1]]<-p
  
  p<-ggplot(data = chicago_map_with_customerTypeCount) +
    geom_sf(aes(fill=( (member)/sum(member) - (casual)/sum(casual) )))+
    scale_fill_gradient2(low = "red",
                         mid = "lightgray",
                         high = "blue",
                         labels = scales::percent_format(),
                         name = "% of relative usage difference: member - casual")+
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))+
    labs(title = glue("Chicago zone relative usage difference between users {contextualisation}"), subtitle = "The difference is calculated as member usage minus casual usage")  
  plots[[2]]<-p
  
  return(plots)
}

Social usage

We consider that, if the user begin their trip in the same minute and station as another user, then he makes a social usage of Cyclistic services.
This measure is far from exact because two user that dont know each others can take a bike in the same minute and station. Or two user that went on a bike trip could take more than a minute to lend the bike, or they could start in different stations and meet while on bike.
However uncertain, the results are interesting. It shows that casuals use socially Cyclistics services 35% of the time while members have a social usage only 20% of the time.

socialData<-processedData[start_station_name!=""] %>% 
  mutate(social = (start_station_name==lag(start_station_name) & abs(difftime(started_at,lag(started_at)))<60) | (start_station_name==lag(start_station_name) & (abs(difftime(started_at,lead(started_at))))<60)) %>%  #Add a social column that is True if the user begins their trip in the same minute and station as another user
  drop_na()

socialMemberPercent = round(mean(socialData[member_casual=="member"]$social), 3)
socialCasualPercent = round(mean(socialData[member_casual=="casual"]$social), 3)

ggplot(socialData, aes(y = member_casual, fill = social)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill")+
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Social Usage")+
  labs(x = "Percentage of social usage", y = "Customer type", title = "Social usage by customer type")+
  geom_vline(xintercept = socialMemberPercent)+
  annotate("text", x = socialMemberPercent, y = 2, label = glue("{socialMemberPercent*100}%"))+
  geom_vline(xintercept = socialCasualPercent)+
  annotate("text", x = socialCasualPercent, y = 1, label = glue("{socialCasualPercent*100}%"))

rm(socialData, socialMemberPercent, socialCasualPercent)

Recommendations

The analysis aims at uncovering the differences between casual and members clients in order to understand what could convince a casual client to become a member client.
The casual offers regroup single-ride and full day pass. This offer is about short term engagement.
The member offer contain annual membership. This offer is about long term engagement.
In order to convert casual clients into member clients, we could try to develop new transition offer that is about mid term engagement. This offer would be developed to be attractive to casual clients while being unattractive to member client since we dont want to convert members into casuals. Based on those reflections and the previously seen data, here is 3 recommendations:

  • Creation of a summer pass since its the season that interest casual the most. The member shall keep its current offer to have access to the service during the whole year.
  • Creation of an annual leisure pass that gives:

    • full access during weekends

    • access between 19h-5h during workweek

      Those time ranges interest the casuals. The member shall keep his current offer to have access to the two commuting time range.

  • On annual passes, allow the member to loan a 2nd bike for free ~3 times per week. This could make long time offers more attractive to casuals and at the same times it is a way for non customers to test the service in very favorable conditions (social usage).
